        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">China has set an ambitious 5% GDP growth target for 2025 despite escalating trade tensions with the US and a slowing domestic economy. In a speech at the National People’s Congress (NPC), Premier Li Qiang acknowledged <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-06-03-2025-h1-1-growing-economic-challenges?source=website" target="_blank">growing economic challenges</a>, especially since Trump instilled higher tariffs this week. Other problems include consumer demand and a struggling property sector.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;filter:blur(5px);">To counter these pressures, China raised its budget deficit to 4% of its GDP, the highest in decades, and pledged greater fiscal support. It also lowered its inflation target to 2%, reflecting concerns over deflation. Beijing also remains committed to high-tech self-sufficiency. It vows to expand investment in AI, quantum technology, and 6G. 
       </p>
        </mj-text>
